    "longAnswer": [
      {
        "question": "Define Alcohols and Phenols. Provide one example of each with its IUPAC name, and explain why they are considered distinct classes despite both containing the -OH group. (5 Marks)",
        "answer": "**Definition:**\n- **Alcohol**: Organic compound where a hydroxyl (-OH) group is bonded to an aliphatic carbon atom.\n- **Phenol**: Organic compound where a hydroxyl (-OH) group is directly bonded to an aromatic benzene ring.\n\n**Examples & Names:**\n1. Ethanol (CH3CH2-OH): An alcohol derived from ethane.\n2. Phenol (C6H5-OH): The simplest phenol, where OH replaces H on a benzene ring.\n\n**Distinction:**\nThey are distinct because the carbon atom holding the -OH group differs in hybridization and environment:\n- In alcohols, C is sp3 hybridized (saturated), leading to specific reactivity patterns like oxidation to carbonyls.\n- In phenols, C is sp2 hybridized (aromatic), making the compound more acidic and reactive towards electrophilic substitution due to resonance with the ring. This structural difference fundamentally alters their chemical behavior.",
